Hydrogen bonds are a type of noncovalent bond that form between an electropositive hydrogen atom and two electronegative atoms, typically nitrogen, oxygen, or fluorine. These bonds are relatively weak, with a strength of about 5-10% that of a covalent bond, but they play a crucial role in the stability of many biological molecules, such as DNA and proteins. The hydrogen bond forms when the partial positive charge on the hydrogen atom is attracted to the partial negative charge on the electronegative atom. This results in the hydrogen atom being "shared" between the two atoms, creating a bond. The hydrogen bond is directional, meaning that it forms only when the atoms are oriented in a specific way relative to each other. This specificity allows hydrogen bonds to play a key role in the structure and function of many biological molecules.

